<span id="freeTextContainer14479406106177220559">thank y’all for the recommendation to read Radical Belonging! I’ve added it to my list. I’ve also really enjoyed Staci Haines’ The Politics of Trauma,</span>
  <span id="freeText14479406106177220559" style="display:none">thank y’all for the recommendation to read Radical Belonging! I’ve added it to my list. I’ve also really enjoyed Staci Haines’ The Politics of Trauma, Renee Linklater’s Decolonizing Trauma Work, and Aurora Morales Levins’ Kindling for similarly to Menakem working to tackle this beast of writing about trauma healing with an analysis of the ways systems of oppression inflict trauma. I do think “My Grandmother’s Hands” is a valuable contribution to trauma lit, so I hope folks who haven’t will still read it — I don’t think any single one of these books covers it all, or covers it perfectly, but...the more, the merrier right? :)</span>
