  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4491251803" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4491251803" />
    <a title="Jeanne" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7743315-jeanne"><img alt="Jeanne" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1609344390p2/7743315.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4491251803?book_show_action=true">Jan 26, 2022</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jeanne" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jeanne" href="/user/show/7743315-jeanne">Jeanne</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/36167466-my-grandmother-s-hands">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7743315-jeanne?shelf=psychology">psychology</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7743315-jeanne?shelf=african-african-american">african-african-american</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7743315-jeanne?shelf=read-2022">read-2022</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7743315-jeanne?shelf=trauma">trauma</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4491251803" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5409926499856419821">I was initially uncomfortable in reading <em>My Grandmother&apos;s Hands</em>, as Menakem&apos;s language was not typical scholarly language (e.g., he referred to the vagus nerve as the &quot;soul nerve&quot;). I initially resisted some of his ideas, in part because <em>My Grandmother&apos;s Hands</em> is more somatically-oriented than I am. I eventually got to a place where I acknowledged that there may be several paths to the same destination and that it is useful for all of us to have multiple tools for responding to trauma and stress</span>
  <span id="freeText5409926499856419821" style="display:none">I was initially uncomfortable in reading <em>My Grandmother's Hands</em>, as Menakem's language was not typical scholarly language (e.g., he referred to the vagus nerve as the "soul nerve"). I initially resisted some of his ideas, in part because <em>My Grandmother's Hands</em> is more somatically-oriented than I am. I eventually got to a place where I acknowledged that there may be several paths to the same destination and that it is useful for all of us to have multiple tools for responding to trauma and stressors. Body, mind, emotions, behaviors each impact each other; intervention in any one place impacts all. <br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1643216385i/32495212._SX540_.png" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br>Source: <a href="https://torontopsychology.com/approach/cognitive-behaviour-therapy-cbt/" rel="nofollow noopener">Toronto Psychology Clinic</a><br><br>I quibble with whether we need to start with the body to produce healing from racial trauma, but I do believe it is a helpful place to start, especially as so many of us tend to be too much up in our heads, especially after being traumatized.<br><br>At any rate, <em>My Grandmother's Hands</em> is insightful, hopeful, experiential, and useful. I particularly liked his distinction between clean and dirty pain, which is not new, but nonetheless helpful. He described clean pain as "pain that mends and can build your capacity for growth. It’s the pain you experience when you know, exactly, what you need to say or do; when you really, really don’t want to say or do it; and when you do it anyway" (p. 19). On the other hand, dirty pain is the "pain of avoidance, blame, and denial. When people respond from their most wounded parts, become cruel or violent, or physically or emotionally run away, they experience dirty pain. They also create more of it for themselves and others" (p. 20). These aren't new ideas, but they are helpfully described ideas.<br><br>What I liked about this book is that Menakem very clearly and specifically wrote for, using his words, "white bodies," "black bodies," and police officers. His chapters were readable and, although he never tippy-toed around issues or avoided them, he likely didn't write in a way that was off-putting to his audience. <br><br>Menakem talked about the Five Anchors as ways of settling traumatized bodies – and all of us are traumatized from his point of view – in a way that reminded me of Tara Brach's description of RAIN (Recognize, Allow, Investigate, Nurture). These anchors allow us become and remain centered:<br><br><strong>Anchor 1:</strong> Soothe yourself to quiet your mind, calm your heart, and settle your body. <br><strong>Anchor 2:</strong> Simply notice the sensations, vibrations, and emotions in your body instead of reacting to them. <br><strong>Anchor 3:</strong> Accept the discomfort—and notice when it changes—instead of trying to flee from it. <br><strong>Anchor 4:</strong> Stay present and in your body as you move through the unfolding experience, with all its ambiguity and uncertainty, and respond from the best parts of yourself. <br><strong>Anchor 5:</strong> Safely discharge any energy that remains. (p. 168)<br><br>We need to be present and settled and centered if we want to effectively work through our own pain or someone else's. We need to be present and settled and centered if we want to prevent problems from escalating. Menakem provides a nice path for being able to do so.<br><br>Menakem, who lives in Minnesota, has offered a number of trainings for the Minneapolis Police. I wonder about Derek Chauvin, as well as his peers, who didn't intervene to prevent George Floyd's death. It would seem that such a training needs to be more fairly intensive and offered across time to be effective – not just for the police but all of us.<br><br>I read this with a professional organization's book club. Our discussions have, so far, been spirited and positive.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5409926499856419821" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

